WEBVTT

00:06.298 --> 00:09.092
(orchestra playing patriotic,
Romantic Russian‐themed music)

01:03.355 --> 01:05.065
(music fades)

01:07.609 --> 01:09.236
♪ ♪

01:14.533 --> 01:15.533
(laughter, chatter)

01:18.704 --> 01:20.162
Oh, man.

01:20.163 --> 01:22.582
So, uh, as to, uh...

01:22.583 --> 01:25.042
We're gonna sit here,
Mr. Putin.

01:25.043 --> 01:26.085
I'm gonna sit here.

01:26.086 --> 01:28.629
I will come around,
and we can meet here.

01:28.630 --> 01:31.341
♪ ♪

01:32.884 --> 01:34.176
Stone: We'll meet about here.

01:34.177 --> 01:36.387
Translator:
descend from the balcony.

01:36.388 --> 01:37.847
‐I like it better
from there...
‐Okay.

01:37.848 --> 01:38.889
'cause it gives you some depth.

01:38.890 --> 01:40.770
In fact, there's a bar
back there if you'd like.

01:42.394 --> 01:44.061
No, further back, further back.

01:44.062 --> 01:45.062
Okay.

01:48.734 --> 01:50.694
All right, ready?

01:51.611 --> 01:53.696
Now pretend like
we don't know each other.

01:53.697 --> 01:56.741
And we're‐‐
Pretend we haven't seen
each other in months.

01:56.742 --> 01:59.244
Okay. And action.

02:02.080 --> 02:03.165
Action.

02:03.999 --> 02:05.583
Tell him "action" in Russian.

02:05.584 --> 02:07.918
(translating)

02:07.919 --> 02:09.795
(softly)
Okay.

02:09.796 --> 02:12.465
Where's my AD? Come on.

02:12.466 --> 02:14.342
Action!

02:14.343 --> 02:16.093
Stone: He went
into another meeting.

02:16.094 --> 02:17.638
Oh, there he is.

02:21.224 --> 02:22.516
Oh, that's very kind of you.

02:22.517 --> 02:23.768
Here.
(chuckles)

02:23.769 --> 02:25.686
Thank you,
Mr. President.

02:25.687 --> 02:28.105
How have you been?
It's been a long time.

02:28.106 --> 02:29.357
‐Sugar.
‐Sugar?

02:29.358 --> 02:30.687
Without sugar here.

02:30.688 --> 02:33.611
♪ ♪

02:33.612 --> 02:35.905
Uh, it's been quite
a lot of activity

02:35.906 --> 02:38.949
the last few months.

02:38.950 --> 02:40.076
My country, uh,

02:40.077 --> 02:41.870
America has had an election.

02:44.122 --> 02:47.667
(chuckles)
Donald Trump won.

02:47.668 --> 02:49.210
This...

02:49.211 --> 02:51.045
This is your fourth president.

02:51.046 --> 02:51.797
Am I right?
Your fourth president.

02:51.798 --> 02:54.882
<i>Mr. Clinton...</i>

02:54.883 --> 02:55.883
<i>Mr. Bush...</i>

02:57.427 --> 02:59.220
<i>Mr. Obama, and now,</i>

02:59.221 --> 03:00.597
the fourth one.

03:03.183 --> 03:04.476
What changes?

03:08.146 --> 03:09.605
(chuckles)

03:09.606 --> 03:11.806
Is that your feeling,
in between all
the four presidents?

03:23.704 --> 03:25.830
Stone: Yeah.

03:25.831 --> 03:28.207
Is there any possibility,
a hope of change

03:28.208 --> 03:29.208
with Mr. Trump?

03:36.007 --> 03:37.925
Wow. That's very Russian.

03:37.926 --> 03:40.469
Very Dostoyevsky.

03:40.470 --> 03:41.805
(chuckles)

03:43.265 --> 03:45.474
Hillary Clinton:
<i>Vladimir Putin himself</i>

03:45.475 --> 03:47.601
<i>directed the covert
cyberattacks.</i>

03:47.602 --> 03:52.481
<i>This is not just an attack
against me and my campaign,</i>

03:52.482 --> 03:54.233
<i>this is an attack
against our country.</i>

03:54.234 --> 03:57.862
US intelligence believes
that the cyberattack

03:57.863 --> 04:01.282
on the e‐mail
of the Democratic
National Committee

04:01.283 --> 04:05.494
<i>was ordered by</i>
<i>the Russian president himself,</i>
<i>Vladimir Putin.</i>

04:05.495 --> 04:06.413
In early September, when I saw

04:06.414 --> 04:09.707
when I saw
President Putin
in China,

04:09.708 --> 04:13.043
I felt that
the most effective way

04:13.044 --> 04:15.547
to ensure that
that didn't happen...

04:16.590 --> 04:18.716
was to talk to him directly.

04:18.717 --> 04:20.468
And tell him to cut it out,
and there were gonna be

04:20.469 --> 04:22.595
some serious consequences
if he didn't.

04:22.596 --> 04:25.306
Stone: The election has been
heavily criticized.

04:25.307 --> 04:28.934
And the narrative
as written by the West

04:28.935 --> 04:31.479
has now become that Russia

04:31.480 --> 04:34.733
interfered in this election,
to the benefit of Mr. Trump.

04:56.963 --> 04:58.882
(clears throat)

05:06.264 --> 05:07.933
♪ ♪

05:21.154 --> 05:23.615
Yes. So why, why did you bother
to hack the election then?

06:39.024 --> 06:41.192
Sadly...

06:42.569 --> 06:44.571
the American Dream...

06:44.988 --> 06:46.865
is dead.

07:18.980 --> 07:21.274
(chuckles)

07:24.194 --> 07:26.362
Donald J. Trump is calling

07:26.363 --> 07:29.114
or a total and complete shutdown

07:29.115 --> 07:32.242
of Muslims entering
the United States,

07:32.243 --> 07:34.662
until our country's
representatives

07:34.663 --> 07:39.291
can figure out
what the hell is going on.

07:39.292 --> 07:42.087
Build that wall!
Build that wall!

08:22.460 --> 08:25.295
But, you know,
even Trump has said

08:25.296 --> 08:26.630
the Russians hacked
the election. That was a quote.

08:26.631 --> 08:30.092
As far as hacking,
I think it was Russia,

08:30.093 --> 08:32.386
but I think we also get hacked

08:32.387 --> 08:35.348
by other countries
and other people.

09:04.461 --> 09:07.671
If Putin likes Donald Trump,
guess what folks?

09:07.672 --> 09:10.716
That's called an asset,
not a liability.

09:10.717 --> 09:13.093
Now, I don't know
that I'm gonna get along

09:13.094 --> 09:14.845
with Vladimir Putin.

09:14.846 --> 09:19.224
I hope I do, but there's
a good chance I won't.

09:19.225 --> 09:21.810
And if I don't,
do you honestly believe

09:21.811 --> 09:23.687
that Hillary would be tougher
on Putin than me?

09:23.688 --> 09:26.940
Does anybody in this room
really believe that?

09:26.941 --> 09:29.943
Stone:
Well, this all seems to me
still historically enormous.

09:29.944 --> 09:33.739
I've never seen where
the two leading parties,

09:33.740 --> 09:37.576
the intelligence agencies,
FBI, CIA, NSA,

09:37.577 --> 09:41.038
and, uh, the political
leadership of NATO

09:41.039 --> 09:42.999
believe this story
that Russia hacked
the election.

09:44.751 --> 09:46.252
It's enormous. I mean...

09:53.468 --> 09:55.053
Have you read
the 25‐page report?

09:56.679 --> 09:59.723
Newswoman: <i>It details
Russian cyberattacks</i>

09:59.724 --> 10:01.308
<i>against not just the
Democratic National Committee,</i>

10:01.309 --> 10:03.644
<i>but the White House</i>

10:03.645 --> 10:05.145
<i>the Joint Chiefs of Staff,</i>

10:05.146 --> 10:06.313
<i>the State Department,</i>

10:06.314 --> 10:07.397
<i>even American companies.</i>

10:07.398 --> 10:10.150
<i>Some hacks, successful.</i>

10:10.151 --> 10:11.151
<i>Others, thwarted.</i>

10:53.611 --> 10:58.240
And, uh, it seems,
Senator McCain for example,
today or yesterday,

10:58.241 --> 10:59.950
was proposing a veto,
a Senate veto,

10:59.951 --> 11:04.706
of any lifting of sanctions
from Trump, in advance.

11:12.672 --> 11:13.464
John McCain:
<i>Putin is a killer.</i>

11:13.465 --> 11:15.924
There is no moral equivalence

11:15.925 --> 11:19.761
between
the United States
and Putin's Russia.

11:19.762 --> 11:23.307
I repeat, there is
no moral equivalent

11:23.308 --> 11:26.268
between that butcher
and thug and KGB colonel

11:26.269 --> 11:29.688
and the United States
of America, the country...

11:29.689 --> 11:31.889
that Ronald Reagan
used to call a shining
city on a hill.

11:59.886 --> 12:02.764
Stone:
"Carthage must be destroyed."

12:51.020 --> 12:53.563
Stone:
Russia has been accused
of enormous treachery now.

12:53.564 --> 12:56.108
This is a major charge.

12:56.109 --> 12:58.235
The media repeats it
and repeats it,

12:58.236 --> 12:59.695
and it seems to have entered
into the lexicon
in the United States.

12:59.696 --> 13:01.989
It's just taken for granted.

13:01.990 --> 13:04.116
You can say Russia hacked
the election,

13:04.117 --> 13:06.410
and many people say
Trump is, uh,

13:06.411 --> 13:08.912
in the Kremlin's pocket,
has a debt to the Kremlin.

13:08.913 --> 13:11.873
So you, you see
where this leads to.

13:11.874 --> 13:15.752
It makes a situation impossible,
very difficult for Mr. Trump,

13:15.753 --> 13:17.546
if indeed he intends
to correct relations,

13:17.547 --> 13:19.841
to reset relations.

13:57.420 --> 13:59.796
Many people are frustrated,
who agree

13:59.797 --> 14:03.091
that this hacking charge
is fraudulent.

14:03.092 --> 14:04.217
Many people agree
with Julian Assange,

14:04.218 --> 14:08.638
<i>who has a pretty solid record
going back to 2006.</i>

14:08.639 --> 14:12.309
We can say, um,
we have said, repeatedly,

14:12.310 --> 14:13.518
uh, over the last two months,

14:13.519 --> 14:18.398
uh, that our source, uh,
is not the Russian government,

14:18.399 --> 14:20.109
uh, and it is not state party.

14:48.012 --> 14:50.138
Well, it seems to me that
if you know their tricks,
you could make

14:50.139 --> 14:52.933
some kind of statement
about cyberwarfare

14:52.934 --> 14:57.020
and give specifics
of why this was not possible,

14:57.021 --> 14:58.563
and why there
should have been a trace.

14:58.564 --> 15:01.942
I mean, there's many different
avenues you can explore.

15:01.943 --> 15:04.152
It seems as if
Russia doesn't care

15:04.153 --> 15:07.322
about defending itself
to these accusations.

15:07.323 --> 15:11.285
They're letting them fly by
and saying business as usual.

15:51.367 --> 15:55.162
Well, is there any evidence,
uh, in cyberspace

15:55.163 --> 15:57.874
that Russia can present
in its defense?

16:18.477 --> 16:20.854
So, right now,
he's waiting it out.

16:20.855 --> 16:23.773
At the same time, you know,
Mr. Trump has called,
on more than one occasion,

16:23.774 --> 16:29.321
for another massive US military
buildup in both nuclear
and conventional,

16:29.322 --> 16:30.906
<i>which makes no sense to me.</i>

16:30.907 --> 16:33.451
<i>I mean, how can America spend
more than it's already spending?</i>

16:34.577 --> 16:36.204
(Putin speaking)

17:10.738 --> 17:13.240
Do you have any hopes
of a meeting, uh,

17:13.241 --> 17:15.910
sometime in the coming months
with Mr. Trump?

17:45.398 --> 17:48.692
But how is he going to work
with the intelligence agencies
if the intelligence agencies

17:48.693 --> 17:50.819
are telling him that
Russia hacked the election?

17:50.820 --> 17:52.154
It's a dead end.

17:58.035 --> 18:00.036
If, uh, Mr. Trump called for...

18:00.037 --> 18:05.166
wanted to declassify
or see the files on Ukraine,

18:05.167 --> 18:08.086
all the files,
all the files on Syria,

18:08.087 --> 18:10.755
and see the origins
of these problems,

18:10.756 --> 18:12.090
is there a possibility of that,

18:12.091 --> 18:14.385
that he might change
some of his thinking?

19:11.651 --> 19:13.527
When is the next G20 meeting?

19:16.864 --> 19:20.264
So that, theoretically, would be
the first time they'd ever see
each other if they did?

19:22.578 --> 19:24.789
I gather you've had
two phone calls with him?

19:28.918 --> 19:31.461
And I gather, uh...

19:31.462 --> 19:33.302
some of the talk may
have been about terrorism?

19:52.024 --> 19:55.860
Right. Right.
I understand.

19:55.861 --> 19:59.072
Uh... was there
US interference

19:59.073 --> 20:03.828
in the 2012 election in Russia?

20:31.772 --> 20:34.149
We have programs both inside
Russia and outside Russia.

20:34.150 --> 20:37.652
To work with those
Russian activists

20:37.653 --> 20:40.530
who want to work with us,
to try to strengthen
rule of law,

20:40.531 --> 20:43.241
to try to strengthen
a free press.

20:43.242 --> 20:45.034
We have a large number
of Russian journalists

20:45.035 --> 20:47.495
who've actually fled this,
uh, fled Russia now,

20:47.496 --> 20:50.957
who are working with us
and with others in Europe,

20:50.958 --> 20:54.377
to try to ensure there is,

20:54.378 --> 20:57.756
um, independent
Russian language news,

20:57.757 --> 20:59.841
uh, inside‐‐ going back
into the country.

20:59.842 --> 21:02.594
We also work on lege‐‐
uh, LGBT rights

21:02.595 --> 21:04.137
and other things inside Russia

21:04.138 --> 21:05.639
with those who want
to work with us.

21:23.032 --> 21:24.158
(sighs)

21:48.432 --> 21:49.891
(translating)

21:49.892 --> 21:53.729
Yes. Was there
cyberinterference
in the 2012 election?

22:10.788 --> 22:14.791
Let's clarify it,
'cause cyberwarfare
is here with us.

22:14.792 --> 22:17.710
We've started
down that road
a few years ago.

22:17.711 --> 22:21.464
We have entered into
a new phase of conflict,

22:21.465 --> 22:26.177
in which we use a cyberweapon
to create physical destruction.

22:26.178 --> 22:27.303
In the movie I did, <i>Snowden,</i>
there's a scene‐‐

22:27.304 --> 22:30.139
and Snowden, uh,
told me this story‐‐

22:30.140 --> 22:32.225
<i>he's in Japan.</i>

22:32.226 --> 22:35.103
Snowden:
<i>NSA wanted to impress</i>
<i>the Japanese,</i>

22:35.104 --> 22:36.564
<i>show them our reach.</i>

22:39.817 --> 22:43.152
<i>They were not as thrilled
to learn that we wanted them</i>

22:43.153 --> 22:45.406
<i>to help us spy
on the Japanese population.</i>

22:46.782 --> 22:48.450
<i>They said it was
against their laws.</i>

22:50.578 --> 22:52.788
<i>Of course, we tapped
the entire country anyway.</i>

22:54.039 --> 22:55.957
<i>And we didn't stop there,</i>

22:55.958 --> 22:58.042
<i>'cause once we owned
their communications system,</i>

22:58.043 --> 23:00.962
<i>we started going after
the physical infrastructure.</i>

23:00.963 --> 23:06.259
<i>We'd slip these little</i>
<i>sleeper programs into</i>
<i>power grids, dams,</i>

23:06.260 --> 23:09.512
<i>hospitals, and the idea was,
if the day came</i>

23:09.513 --> 23:12.056
<i>when Japan was
no longer an ally,</i>

23:12.057 --> 23:13.057
<i>it'd be lights out.</i>

23:16.729 --> 23:18.313
<i>And it wasn't just the Japanese.</i>

23:18.314 --> 23:21.524
<i>We were planting malware
in Mexico, Germany,</i>

23:21.525 --> 23:24.777
<i>Brazil, Austria.</i>

23:24.778 --> 23:26.529
<i>I mean, China I can understand,</i>

23:26.530 --> 23:28.239
<i>or Russia or Iran,</i>

23:28.240 --> 23:30.199
<i>Venezuela, okay, but...</i>

23:30.200 --> 23:32.577
<i>‐Austria?</i>
‐(bell tinkles)

23:32.578 --> 23:36.039
<i>You're also being ordered
to follow most world leaders</i>

23:36.040 --> 23:37.665
<i>and heads of industry.</i>

23:37.666 --> 23:39.876
<i>You know,
you're tracking trade deals,</i>

23:39.877 --> 23:42.837
<i>sex scandals, diplomatic cables</i>

23:42.838 --> 23:45.673
<i>to give the US an advantage
in negotiations at the G8</i>

23:45.674 --> 23:50.303
<i>or leverage
over Brazilian oil companies,</i>

23:50.304 --> 23:53.181
<i>or helping to oust
some third world leader</i>

23:53.182 --> 23:54.557
<i>who's not playing ball.</i>

23:54.558 --> 23:58.227
<i>And ultimately,
the truth sinks in</i>

23:58.228 --> 24:00.313
<i>that no matter</i>
<i>what justification</i>
<i>you're selling yourself,</i>

24:00.314 --> 24:02.524
<i>this is not about terrorism.</i>

24:05.027 --> 24:06.820
<i>Terrorism is the excuse.</i>

24:09.657 --> 24:14.453
<i>This is about economic
and social control.</i>

24:16.080 --> 24:18.498
<i>And the only thing
you're really protecting</i>

24:18.499 --> 24:21.251
<i>is the supremacy
of your government.</i>

24:43.107 --> 24:47.568
If I'm saying that
they're planting malware
in Japanese infrastructure

24:47.569 --> 24:49.654
to destroy
power stations, railroads,

24:49.655 --> 24:52.365
close the country down,
black it out‐‐

24:52.366 --> 24:53.449
the Russians are
miles ahead of me.

24:53.450 --> 24:55.785
They must realize
the dangers here,

24:55.786 --> 24:59.956
and they must've been working
on them for some time,

24:59.957 --> 25:02.333
uh, to prevent such a situation
from happening to Russia,

25:02.334 --> 25:03.793
'cause that would do
the obvious,

25:03.794 --> 25:06.505
one of the obvious enemies
of the United States.

25:33.490 --> 25:35.367
Stone:
Yeah. I buy that.

25:40.039 --> 25:41.540
Yeah.

26:08.192 --> 26:13.362
Okay. Well, we're talking‐‐
I mean, in real time,
we're talking like,

26:13.363 --> 26:15.573
if Snowden is saying
the US is doing this

26:15.574 --> 26:20.161
to an ally in 2007,
with Japan, 2008,

26:20.162 --> 26:23.456
if they're planting
malware in allies‐‐ do you
understand what I'm saying?

26:23.457 --> 26:26.292
What are they doing with their‐‐

26:26.293 --> 26:29.170
people like China,
Russia, Iran, and so forth?

26:29.171 --> 26:32.882
I mean, you understand
my point is that Russia
had to be aware

26:32.883 --> 26:35.718
as early as 2007 that the US

26:35.719 --> 26:36.719
<i>was planting malware.</i>

26:36.720 --> 26:40.098
<i>The United States
will not admit it,</i>

26:40.099 --> 26:41.933
<i>but it's known that in 2010,</i>

26:41.934 --> 26:45.728
<i>we succeeded in planting
the Stuxnet virus in Iran.</i>

26:45.729 --> 26:46.855
(Putin speaking)

26:48.524 --> 26:51.109
Newsman:
<i>By the fall of 2010,</i>

26:51.110 --> 26:56.030
<i>the consensus was that</i>
<i>Iran's top secret uranium</i>
<i>enrichment plant</i>

26:56.031 --> 26:58.241
<i>at Natanz was the target,
and that Stuxnet</i>

26:58.242 --> 27:02.912
<i>was a carefully constructed</i>
<i>weapon, designed to be carried</i>
<i>into the plant</i>

27:02.913 --> 27:05.623
<i>on a corrupted laptop
or thumb drive,</i>

27:05.624 --> 27:08.668
<i>then infect the system,
disguise its presence,</i>

27:08.669 --> 27:10.920
<i>move through the network
changing computer code,</i>

27:10.921 --> 27:14.882
<i>and subtly alter
the speed of the centrifuges</i>

27:14.883 --> 27:16.300
<i>without the Iranians
ever noticing.</i>

27:16.301 --> 27:19.011
<i>Sabotage by software.</i>

27:19.012 --> 27:23.433
Were there attacks on Russia
as early as 2007, '06, '05?

27:33.902 --> 27:34.778
Yeah, yeah.

27:34.779 --> 27:36.738
As late as what year?
As late as...

27:42.160 --> 27:44.037
Stone:
Okay.

27:47.624 --> 27:49.126
Yes.

27:50.335 --> 27:51.879
And then what happened?

27:53.046 --> 27:57.676
I mean, when did Russia
build up its cybercapabilities?

28:33.587 --> 28:36.380
I would imagine Russia
is having an ongoing battle

28:36.381 --> 28:38.341
with the United States,

28:38.342 --> 28:40.718
secret battle,
with cyberwarfare.

28:40.719 --> 28:44.263
I would imagine
United States is trying
to do things to Russia,

28:44.264 --> 28:47.517
and Russia was trying
to defend itself, and do things
to the United States.

28:50.854 --> 28:54.357
(translator speaking)

28:54.358 --> 28:56.150
Stone: Okay.

28:56.151 --> 28:59.362
Well, he's, he's acting funny
about this story.

28:59.363 --> 29:00.488
Like he's guilty a bit.

29:00.489 --> 29:03.033
You look like a fox
who just got out
of the henhouse.

29:10.707 --> 29:13.334
Stone:
A few weeks ago on <i>RT,</i>
I saw a report.

29:13.335 --> 29:16.504
It was not followed up on,
it disappeared after
a day or two,

29:16.505 --> 29:18.255
but in that report,

29:18.256 --> 29:20.132
20 plus countries

29:20.133 --> 29:23.010
were reported as being part
of a botnet attack

29:23.011 --> 29:26.555
on the banking system
in Russia, six major banks.

29:26.556 --> 29:31.394
This seems to be of such
a magnitude that it was‐‐
this was after the election.

29:31.395 --> 29:35.272
It points to a possible
US attack on Russia's
banking system.

29:35.273 --> 29:36.273
(speaking Russian)

29:45.534 --> 29:47.995
(speaking Russian)

30:41.339 --> 30:44.008
It's a gigantic piece
of business.

30:44.009 --> 30:47.011
I mean, you have Mr. Biden,
first of all, who says,

30:47.012 --> 30:49.263
we will attack Russia
in the same manner

30:49.264 --> 30:51.307
as they attacked us
in this election.

30:51.308 --> 30:53.018
We're sending a message.

30:54.770 --> 30:57.271
We have the capacity to do it

30:57.272 --> 30:58.981
and he'll know it,

30:58.982 --> 31:00.316
and it'll be at the time
of our choosing

31:00.317 --> 31:03.819
and under the circumstances
that have the greatest impact.

31:03.820 --> 31:05.821
And Mr. Obama
seconded that.

31:05.822 --> 31:08.949
I think there is no doubt

31:08.950 --> 31:14.580
that when any foreign government
tries to impact

31:14.581 --> 31:15.831
the integrity of our elections

31:15.832 --> 31:20.336
that... we need to take action.

31:20.337 --> 31:22.588
And we will, at a time and place
of our own choosing.

31:22.589 --> 31:26.342
Some of it may be, uh,

31:26.343 --> 31:30.262
explicit, and publicized,
some of it may not be.

31:30.263 --> 31:34.058
Um, but Mr. Putin is
well aware of my feelings
about this,

31:34.059 --> 31:35.643
because I spoke
to him directly about it.

31:35.644 --> 31:39.647
This is outrageous conversation,
but those are big words.

31:39.648 --> 31:42.191
They're from the vice president,
and then from the president.

31:42.192 --> 31:44.026
They're serious people.

31:44.027 --> 31:47.364
So something happened
before inauguration day.

32:26.319 --> 32:29.280
Well, you're making
light of it, but in view
of how much money

32:29.281 --> 32:33.367
we have invested
in cyberwarfare
and our cybercommand,

32:33.368 --> 32:35.244
it seems like
a serious threat to me.

32:35.245 --> 32:37.872
I have the feeling
that he's playing it down,

32:37.873 --> 32:39.665
because something did happen,

32:39.666 --> 32:41.917
and he doesn't want
to reveal it,

32:41.918 --> 32:45.213
and... because
of sensitive relations.

32:53.263 --> 32:55.973
No. I'm worried that,
you know, I would hate‐‐

32:55.974 --> 32:59.476
I believe that cyberwarfare
can lead to a hot war.

32:59.477 --> 33:01.478
Uh, I, I really believe that,

33:01.479 --> 33:03.772
because of the past.

33:03.773 --> 33:07.359
The Stuxnet virus came
very close to creating chaos
in the world.

33:07.360 --> 33:10.738
I think this is
very dangerous,
very dangerous,

33:10.739 --> 33:12.657
and I think
we're playing with fire.

33:13.867 --> 33:15.619
(Stone laughs)

33:16.870 --> 33:20.080
I know. Well, you're obviously
sitting on some information.

33:20.081 --> 33:22.374
I understand why
you may not want
to make it public.

33:22.375 --> 33:26.086
But are we gonna be able
to handle the capabilities
of this?

33:26.087 --> 33:28.464
It seems to me that
what happened in Iran

33:28.465 --> 33:32.509
could be as serious
in its way as
what happened in 1945

33:32.510 --> 33:34.136
at Nagasaki and Hiroshima.

33:34.137 --> 33:35.457
It was the beginning
of a new age.

34:23.937 --> 34:25.938
It seems to me it's secret war,

34:25.939 --> 34:28.065
but no one knows who started it,

34:28.066 --> 34:31.527
no one knows if it was
a proxy country,

34:31.528 --> 34:33.696
if it was North Korea
that hacked Sony,

34:33.697 --> 34:36.282
that, you know,
these rumors go around.

34:36.283 --> 34:39.201
But if all the lights go out
in Russia overnight,
there'd be a tremendous fear

34:39.202 --> 34:42.413
in Russia, as there would be
in the United States,

34:42.414 --> 34:44.082
and people wouldn't know
who did it.

34:47.544 --> 34:49.754
(laughs) Oh!

35:09.232 --> 35:10.358
Yeah.

35:13.361 --> 35:14.361
A treaty.

35:42.015 --> 35:44.850
Perhaps this is something
that Mr. Trump and
Mr. Putin can really open up.

35:44.851 --> 35:47.145
(Putin speaking)

35:52.984 --> 35:54.986
♪ ♪

35:56.529 --> 35:59.281
(patriotic Russian song playing)

35:59.282 --> 36:02.576
Stone: John Reed,
the only American buried
in the Kremlin.

36:02.577 --> 36:04.578
Played by Warren Beatty
in the wonderful movie <i>Reds.</i>

36:04.579 --> 36:08.916
He wrote about the revolution.
He was here in 1917‐18.

36:08.917 --> 36:11.585
He cared deeply about socialism

36:11.586 --> 36:13.504
and founded the American
Communist Party.

36:13.505 --> 36:16.882
Not that that was evil
or anything, it was
quite idealistic,

36:16.883 --> 36:20.928
'cause it was a worker's‐‐
the workers had a lot of strikes
going on in the US,

36:20.929 --> 36:24.431
and there was
a lot of opposition
from the corporations.

36:24.432 --> 36:26.225
And he was considered a hero

36:26.226 --> 36:27.477
<i>by many, many people.</i>

36:29.646 --> 36:31.313
Of course,
he was against World War I,

36:31.314 --> 36:34.817
as were many pacifists
and decent people.

36:34.818 --> 36:36.485
And out of World War I
came the Russian Revolution,

36:36.486 --> 36:41.448
which is an interesting comment
on the role of empires.

36:41.449 --> 36:43.742
Now we're coming up
onto Lenin's tomb.

36:43.743 --> 36:47.162
I visited here many years ago,
but regulations don't permit us

36:47.163 --> 36:50.624
to go in
and photograph anything.

36:50.625 --> 36:53.669
You know, the interesting issue
about Lenin's tomb

36:53.670 --> 36:57.881
is the fact that, uh, next year
is the hundredth anniversary

36:57.882 --> 36:59.925
<i>of the revolution.</i>

36:59.926 --> 37:01.552
<i>So, this is a big event.</i>

37:01.553 --> 37:05.139
<i>Many people revere him in all
the cities of the Soviet Union,</i>

37:05.140 --> 37:08.308
<i>He has many, many statues.</i>

37:08.309 --> 37:12.938
On the other hand,
with the failure
of Communism in 1991

37:12.939 --> 37:15.691
and the resulting pain
to the population,

37:15.692 --> 37:18.110
there's also
very divided feelings about

37:18.111 --> 37:20.863
whether to honor him
on the hundredth anniversary
or not.

37:20.864 --> 37:22.156
It's a good time
to maybe let him go,

37:22.157 --> 37:25.617
because if indeed his karma's
in here, and he's in a grave,

37:25.618 --> 37:28.495
I would hate‐‐
I'd hate to think
I'd have to hang around

37:28.496 --> 37:31.999
a hundred more years
and be watched by everybody.

37:32.000 --> 37:34.668
I think you'd get‐‐
you should get
a moment off, you know?

37:34.669 --> 37:38.756
So that you can go off
and ingest a new karma.

37:38.757 --> 37:43.635
When you go in, it's a very...
it's a very austere experience.

37:43.636 --> 37:48.307
They keep it quiet.
There's a guard that's
always there, uh, or two.

37:48.308 --> 37:51.101
Uh, and, uh, you have a little,
you're not rushed

37:51.102 --> 37:53.061
like in a lot of places,
you're rushed around a lot.

37:53.062 --> 37:55.647
They give you time, and you,

37:55.648 --> 37:58.567
you sit, you watch,
you listen, you think.

37:58.568 --> 38:00.569
It's a very powerful experience.

38:00.570 --> 38:02.530
(patriotic Russian song playing)

38:05.700 --> 38:06.618
Brezhnev.

38:06.619 --> 38:09.411
‐Felix Dzerzhinsky.
‐Man: Dzerzhinsky.

38:09.412 --> 38:10.579
‐Andropov.
‐Yuri Andropov.

38:10.580 --> 38:14.833
The most famous, uh, villain
in history next to Adolf

38:14.834 --> 38:17.336
according to many people,
Joseph Stalin.

38:17.337 --> 38:20.047
To the people on the,
of the revolution

38:20.048 --> 38:25.010
on the left, for which, uh,
Communism meant a change,

38:25.011 --> 38:27.638
better change for the workers,
he was a disaster in the sense

38:27.639 --> 38:32.100
<i>that he left</i>
<i>a horrible reputation,</i>
<i>uh, and stained</i>

38:32.101 --> 38:33.602
the ideology forever.

38:33.603 --> 38:38.607
Uh... it's mixed with blood
and, and terror.

38:38.608 --> 38:42.736
But he did play a huge role
in World War II and was
a very close ally

38:42.737 --> 38:45.155
with, uh, the US
during World War II.

38:45.156 --> 38:47.533
Mr. Trotsky, no?
Where is he? Ask‐‐

38:47.534 --> 38:49.117
No Trotsky, right?

38:49.118 --> 38:53.121
Stalin, uh, managed to erase,
uh, Trotsky's memory.

38:53.122 --> 38:57.376
He ended up being killed
in Mexico by Stalin's agents.

38:57.377 --> 38:57.794
Let's go.

38:57.795 --> 39:00.963
♪ ♪

39:00.964 --> 39:03.590
Stone:
<i>On Stalin.</i>
<i>He said that, you know,</i>

39:03.591 --> 39:06.301
he's said negative things
about Stalin,

39:06.302 --> 39:09.096
uh, and of course,
he's widely condemned
in the world.

39:09.097 --> 39:14.643
But, at the same time,
we all know that he lead, uh,
Russia to victory over Germany,

39:14.644 --> 39:16.436
<i>over fascism.</i>

39:16.437 --> 39:18.647
<i>And, uh, what does
he make of that,</i>

39:18.648 --> 39:21.818
by, uh... let's say
that ambiguity?

39:24.195 --> 39:25.989
‐(Putin laughs) ‐Why?

39:27.156 --> 39:29.033
He can discuss it tomorrow
if he wants.

